\layout Caption

Routines and the corresponding files responsible for the interface dealing
 with imposed constraines.
 The last column states if any extra coding is required when an additional
 constraint is to be added.
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{Table::constraines}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 

We shall first explain the main ideas of very general constraints; then
 linear constrains which are implemented in a rather general way in the
 code will be discussed specifically.
 
\layout Subsubsection

How constrains are dealt with in the code
\layout Standard

Constraints are dealt with in the following general way: every constrained
 equation specifies a single atomic coordinate of some atom (say, coordinate
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 of atom 3, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset 

) which is a function of other coordinates of the same and/or some other
 atoms, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}=\xi(y_{3},z_{1},x_{2})$
\end_inset 

.
 The coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset 

 is then made 
\emph on 
redundand
\emph default 
 and is removed from the optimisation space.
 The consequence of this is that, when calculating the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 in the optimisation space associated with other coordinates which are involved
 in the given constraint, there will be an additional contribution due to
 the constraint.
 In the example above coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{3}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset 

 are involved, so that the energy 
\begin_inset Formula \[
E=E(x_{1},y_{1},z_{1},x_{2},y_{2},z_{2},x_{3}(y_{3},z_{1},x_{2}),y_{3},z_{3})\equiv\widetilde{E}(x_{1},y_{1},z_{1},x_{2},y_{2},z_{2},y_{3},z_{3})\]

\end_inset 

 is a function of all coordinates except for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 associated with this coordinate is not needed during optimisation.
 However, e.g.
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{3}$
\end_inset 

 becomes:
\begin_inset Formula \[
\widetilde{f}_{3y}=-\frac{\partial\widetilde{E}}{\partial y_{3}}=-\frac{\partial E}{\partial y_{3}}-\frac{\partial E}{\partial x_{3}}\frac{\partial x_{3}}{\partial y_{3}}=f_{3y}+f_{3x}\frac{\partial x_{3}}{\partial y_{3}}=f_{3y}+f_{3x}\frac{\partial\xi}{\partial y_{3}}\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3y}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3x}$
\end_inset 

 are the actual (physical) forces on atom 3 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 directions, respectively.
 These are calculated routinely in the code irrespective of the constraints.
 The derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial\xi}{\partial y_{3}}$
\end_inset 

 needed for the calculation of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{3y}$
\end_inset 

 should be calculated analytically for every particular constraint from
 the known function 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset 

 and then coded in in the appropriate places.
 
\layout Standard

There is presently only one important limitation on the atoms involved in
 constraints: a reduntand coordinate must be contained in only one constraint;
 it is not allowed that it is a member of another constraint as well.
 However, other coordinates are allowed to participate in several constraints.
\layout Standard

A note for programmers: coordinates allowed to relax have their relaxation
 flags (
\family typewriter 
iRx
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRy
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRz
\family default 
) fixed to 1; coordinates not allowed to relax have the flags equal to 0;
 redundand coordinates, however, have their flags equal to 2.
 Gradients are calculated for all atoms which have their flags larger than
 zero.
\layout Subsubsection

Linear constraines
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Linear-constraines}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

In the case of linear constraines atomic coordinates of atoms (either different,
 the same or both) may be related linearly to each other.
 Let us collect all those related atomic Cartesian coordinates into a set
 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{i})$
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset 

 is not an atom number, but rather a number in the set).
 Then, the linear relationship between memebers of the set can be expressed
 as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{i}C_{i}r_{i}=0\label{Constraines-view}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset 

 are some constants defined by the nature of the specific constraint.
 Note that not all atoms and all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 components of atomic coordinates may be present.
 In practice several equations like that given above can be supplied.
 Different constraints will be distinguished by an additional index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The simplest example is to allow atoms to move only along certain directions.
 Simply by specifying relaxation flags 
\family typewriter 
iRx
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRy
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRz
\family default 
 in the input (opposite to atomic coordinates, see section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Atomic-Coordinates}

\end_inset 

) one can already allow atoms to move only along 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset 

 axes or in 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $yz$
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $xz$
\end_inset 

 planes; additional constraines are not required in all those cases.
 However, imagine you would like to allow, say, atom 5 to move only along
 the (111) direction, i.e.
 to have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}=y_{5}=z_{5}$
\end_inset 

.
 In this case you will have to specify the following 2 constraints: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{5}-y_{5}=0\,\,\,\textrm{and}\,\,\, z_{5}-y_{5}=0\]

\end_inset 

Obviously, there is only one independent coordinate in this case.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}$
\end_inset 

 is considered as the redundand coordinate from the first constraint and
 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{5}$
\end_inset 

 - from the second (since the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{5}$
\end_inset 

 must not be chosen as a redundand coordinate as it appears in both conditions),
 the only 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

active
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 coordinate in this case will be 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{5}$
\end_inset 

.
 In more complicated cases different atoms may be involved as well.
\layout Standard

The first coordinate in the constraints equations like Eq.
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Constraines-view}

\end_inset 

) with nonzero coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}^{(k)}\neq0$
\end_inset 

, as supplied in the input (section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::constraint-box}

\end_inset 

), is treated automatically as the redundand variable 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}^{(k)}$
\end_inset 

 for the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

.
 This allows to express the redundant variable via all others involved in
 the given constraint 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
r_{1}^{(k)}=-\sum_{i\neq1}^{(k)}\frac{C_{i}^{(k)}}{C_{1}^{(k)}}r_{i}^{(k)}\label{Constraines-view1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

and then calculate the correction 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{j}^{(k)}$
\end_inset 

 to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}_{j}$
\end_inset 

 on any of the nonredundand atoms 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

 due to the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta_{j}^{(k)}=\frac{\partial E}{\partial r_{1}^{(k)}}\frac{\partial r_{1}^{(k)}}{\partial r_{j}}=-f_{1}^{(k)}\frac{C_{i(j)}^{(k)}}{C_{1}^{(k)}}\]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i\equiv i(j)$
\end_inset 

 is the position of atom 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset 

 in the list of atoms involved in the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

.
 The total 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 is obtained by adding corrections 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{j}^{(k)}$
\end_inset 

 due to all constraints to the physical force 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{j}$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Subsubsection

Constant distance between two atoms
\layout Standard

Another simple (but nonlinear) constraint which has been implemented is
 to keep a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset 

, between two atoms constant.
 If, say, atoms 1 and 2 are involved, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 component of the first atom specified in the input (section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::constraint-box}

\end_inset 

) is considered as redundant.
 It is expressed via other coordinates as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{1}=x_{2}\pm\sqrt{d^{2}-(y_{1}-y_{2})^{2}-(z_{1}-z_{2})^{2}}\]

\end_inset 

where two choices of the sign are possible.
 The correction to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

force
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 associated with nonredundand coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{2}$
\end_inset 

 is calculated correspondingly.
\layout Subsubsection

Constant angle between three atoms
\layout Standard

If angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset 

 between three atoms, say atoms 1, 2 and 3, is to be kept constant, then
 the redundand coordinate is choisen to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset 

 coordinate of the first atom in the input (section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::constraint-box}

\end_inset 

).
 It is expressed via other 8 coordinates as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \[
x_{1}=x_{2}+\frac{1}{x_{32}^{2}-r_{32}^{2}\cos^{2}\alpha}\left\{ -x_{32}d\pm\sqrt{\left(x_{32}d\right)^{2}-\left(x_{32}^{2}-r_{32}^{2}\cos^{2}\alpha\right)\left(d^{2}-\Delta_{12}^{2}r_{32}^{2}\cos^{2}\alpha\right)}\right\} \]

\end_inset 

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d=y_{12}y_{32}+z_{12}z_{32}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{12}^{2}=y_{12}^{2}+z_{12}^{2}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{32}^{2}=x_{32}^{2}+y_{32}^{2}+z_{32}^{2}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{32}=x_{3}-x_{2}$
\end_inset 

 , etc.
 The correction to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

forces
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 are straighforward to calculate; they look very cumbersome and not yet
 implemented.
 
\layout Subsection

Molecular Dynamics Algorithms
\layout Standard

If a Molecular Dynamics (MD) simulation is being performed, then the trajectorie
s of atoms are integrated at each timestep using the standard Verlet Leapfrog
 algorithm 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Allen-tildesley}

\end_inset 

 in the NVE ensemble, and a variation of it if a thermostat is used to simulate
 in the NVT ensemble.
 The different algorithms used are described in the following section.
 
\layout Subsubsection

NVE Verlet Leapfrog
\layout Standard

The standard Verlet Leapfrog algorithm first generates new velocities at
 timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $n+\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset 

 from the velocities at timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $n-\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset 

 and the forces on all atoms as follows:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{v}(t+\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\leftarrow\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)+\Delta t\frac{\underline{f}(t)}{m}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Then the positions of all atoms are advanced one timestep based on the new
 velocities:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{r}(t+\Delta t)\leftarrow\underline{r}(t)+\Delta t\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The tempurature of the system at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 is then calculated as the average of the temperatures of the system at
 timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+\frac{1}{2}\Delta t$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

The initial velocities for the system can optionally be provided by the
 user in the input file, however if they are not the program asigns randomly
 oriented velocites to each of the free atoms in the system based on the
 given system temperature, ensuring that the total translational and rotational
 angular momentum of the system is zero.
\layout Subsubsection

NVT with Gaussian Thermostat
\layout Standard

If the system is to be simulated in the NVT ensembe, then the user has the
 choice of four different algothims, the Gaussian thermostat 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{gauss-ts}

\end_inset 

, Berendsen thermostat, the Nose-Hoover thermostat 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{hoover-ts}

\end_inset 

 and stochastic boundary conditions 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{stochastic-md}

\end_inset 

.
 The first of these, the Gaussian constraint thermostat, rescales the velocities
 of atoms at each timestep to achieve a constant system temperature, however
 this algorithm will destroy dynamic correlations very quickly.
 The basic algorithm is detailed below: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{v}(t+\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\leftarrow(2\eta-1)\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)+\eta\Delta t\frac{\underline{f}(t)}{m}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{r}(t+\Delta t)\leftarrow\underline{r}(t)+\Delta t\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\eta=\sqrt{\frac{T_{ext}}{T}}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Where, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset 

 is the temperture at timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

 (that is calculated self consistently with three iterations) and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{ext}$
\end_inset 

 is the given system temperature or bath temperature.
 
\layout Subsubsection

NVT with Berendsen Thermostat
\layout Standard

The Berendsen thermostat is essentially a cross between the NVE and Gaussian
 algorithms that uses a user defined relaxation constant that determines
 the degree of rescaling of the velocities.
 The Berendsen thermostat can be used to push a system towards a desired
 temperture as oppsed to enforcing it.
 The basic algorithm is detailed bellow:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{v}(t+\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\leftarrow\eta\left(\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)+\Delta t\frac{\underline{f}(t)}{m}\right)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\underline{r}(t+\Delta t)\leftarrow\underline{r}(t)+\Delta t\underline{v}(t-\frac{1}{2}\Delta t)\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\eta\leftarrow\sqrt{\left[1+\frac{\Delta t}{\tau}\left(\frac{T_{ext}}{T}-1\right)\right]}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 is the user defined time constant in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $ps$
\end_inset 

.
 As with the Gaussian thermostat, the temperature is calcaulted self consistentl
y over three iterations.
 
\layout Subsubsection

NVT with Nose-Hoover Thermostat
\layout Standard

[
\emph on 
to be added later
\emph default 
]
\layout Subsubsection

Stochastic Boundary Conditions
\layout Standard

To simulate coupling to a heat bath and to physically allow energy gained
 by the system from a moving tip to be carried off to infinity, all or a
 subset (at the boundaries) of the atoms in a system can be subject to a
 random impulse and frictional force at every timestep, governed by the
 Langevin equation:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{\partial\underline{p}_{i}}{\partial t}=-\frac{\partial U}{\partial\underline{q}_{i}}-\gamma\underline{p}_{i}+F^{+}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

 and the atomic momentums and positions respectively, 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset 

 is the total system energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

 is the parametric friction coefficient and 
\begin_inset Formula $F^{+}$
\end_inset 

is a Gaussian distributed random force, the size of which is given by the
 second fluctuation-dissipation theorem:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\left\langle F_{i}^{+}(t_{1})F_{j}^{+}(t_{2})\right\rangle =2\gamma k_{B}T_{ext}\delta_{ij}\delta(t_{1}-t_{2})\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The algorithm used to integrate the equations of motion is the same as the
 Verlet Leapfrog, except that the velocity proportional friction force and
 random impulse is added to the total systematic force prior to the integration.
 The larger the friction coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset 

, the faster the system will react to a change in temperature and as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\rightarrow0$
\end_inset 

 the system tends to the NVE ensemble.
 The code allows the friction coefficient of each degree of freedom in the
 system to be assigned individually by the user in the input file.
 
\layout Standard

It has been demostrated in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{stochastic-md}

\end_inset 

 that this scheme is only valid when the decay time of the friction coefficient
 is much larger than the time step in the simualtion, i.e.
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \[
\Delta t\ll\frac{1}{\gamma}\]

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The code will not prevent or warn the user from using any value for the
 friction coefficient.
 
\layout Subsubsection

Shells
\layout Standard

The code has the facility to treat shells dynamically by one of two separate
 algorithms, which the user selects.
 The first of these the Dynamical Shell model, first introduced in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{shells-dynamic}

\end_inset 

, each shell is given a small mass and the shell motions are integrated
 along with the atomic cores, in a similar way to a di-atomic molecule.
 This method is computationally cheap, however a smaller timestep must be
 used to allow the high frequency core-shell oscillations to be integrated
 accurately.
 Also over long time periods, kinetic energy unphysically leaks in to the
 core-shell degree of freedom, although the program calculates the core-shell
 temperature and so this can be monitored.
 
\layout Standard

The second algorithm, first introduced in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{shell-relax}

\end_inset 

, relaxes the zero-mass shells at each timestep by minimising the system
 energy with respect to shell positions.
 The shells are then removed for the integration, wile the cores are still
 subject the the shell systematic force.
 This algothim is more physical and accurate than the first, however it
 is much more computationally expensive, since a minimisation must take
 place at every timestep.
 
\layout Standard

At the present time these dynamical shell models have only been impemented
 in the NVE ensemble.
 
\layout Section

Virtual AFM 
\layout Subsection

How the virtual machine works
\layout Standard

The virtual AFM was built on the basis of the precise experimental determination
 of the transfer function and impulse response of each element of the real
 AFM in order to reproduce as precisely as possible the experimental behaviours.
 A room temperature commercial AFM/STM 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Omicron}

\end_inset 

 was used with its standard electronic control system, except for the frequency
 demodulator which was replaced by a digital Phase Locked Loop (PLL) based
 frequency demodulator 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Nanosurf}

\end_inset 

.
 The block diagram of the system is shown in figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fFMAFM}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
collapsed false

\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pictures/fmafm.ps
	lyxscale 50
	height 7cm
	keepAspectRatio

\end_inset 


\layout Caption

Schematic of the FM-AFM.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fFMAFM}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 


\layout Standard

FM-AFM involves two control loops: 
\layout Itemize

The first one is supposed to maintain the cantilever oscillation amplitude
 at a preset value 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset 

 (typically from a few nm to tens of nm).
 This is achieved by an Automatic Gain Control block (AGC), which acts on
 the power delivered to the cantilever excitation piezoelectric ceramics.
 This power can be made proportional to the power dissipated by the tip-surface
 interaction by a proper setting of the phase of the excitation drive of
 the cantilever 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{durig-pll,loppacher-phase,pfeiffer-phase}

\end_inset 

.
 It is used to produce dissipation images.
\layout Itemize

The second one is supposed to maintain the resonance frequency shift induced
 by the tip-surface interaction at a preset value 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{c}$
\end_inset 

 (typically from a few Hz to hundreds of Hz).
 This is achieved by an Automatic Distance Control block (ADC), which adjusts
 the tip-surface distance 
\begin_inset Formula $D(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 It is used to produce "topographic" images.
 
\layout Subsubsection

Equation of motion of the cantilever
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Equation-of-motion}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The dynamics of the cantilever is giverned by the following equation of
 motion: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
M\ddot{z}(t)+\frac{M\omega_{0}}{Q}\dot{z}(t)+kz(t)=RA_{pll}\sin(\omega_{pll}t+\varphi)+F_{int}\left(z(t)+D(t);\dot{z}(t)\right)\label{eq:eDynamic}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

It is solved numericacally using the velocity Verlet algorithm
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{verlet-algo}

\end_inset 

.
 In this equation 
\begin_inset Formula $z(t)$
\end_inset 

 is the vertical displacement of the cantileved around its mean value.
 The actual distance of the cantilever from the surface plane is given by
 
\begin_inset Formula $z(t)+D(t)$
\end_inset 

 as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:tip-oscillations}

\end_inset 

.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
collapsed false

\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename xfig.tip.eps
	height 5cm

\end_inset 


\layout Caption

Schematic of the oscilating cantilever system.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{cap:tip-oscillations}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Various terms in the above equation have the following meaning:
\layout Itemize

Terms in the LHS correspond to a damped harmonic oscillator: 
\begin_inset Formula $M=k/\omega_{0}^{2}$
\end_inset 

 is the effective cantilever mass, where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 is cantilever stiffness and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}=2\pi f_{0}$
\end_inset 

 is the resonance frequency of the free cantilever; in addition, there is
 also a friction term in the LHS containing the dimensionless quality factor
 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset 

; these are all intrinsic parameters of the probe.
 
\layout Itemize

The first term in the RHS is the excitation signal which is used to maintain
 the cantilever oscillation amplitude at a preset value 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 The first factor in the excitation amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset 

 is called a damping or dissipation term and is considered in section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Amplitude-regulation}

\end_inset 

 in more detail.
 It's just a variable gain.
 Note that the other part of the signal, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{pll}\sin(\omega_{pll}t+\varphi)$
\end_inset 

, is produced by the PLL as described in more detail in sections 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Amplitude-regulation}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sub:Frequency-demodulation}

\end_inset 

.
 It drives the piezo of the cantilever.
\layout Itemize


\begin_inset Formula $F_{int}\left(z(t)+D(t);\dot{z}(t)\right)$
\end_inset 

 corresponds to the conservative and dissipative interactions between the
 tip and the surface (the latter is not implemented presently).
\layout Subsubsection

Amplitude regulation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Amplitude-regulation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Amplitude regulation is achieved by the Automatic Gain Control (see figure
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fAGC}

\end_inset 

).
 The modulus 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset 

 of the cantilever oscillation 
\begin_inset Formula $z(t)$
\end_inset 

 is extracted by a diode followed by a first-order low-pass filter, modelized
 by:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
A(t)=\frac{\pi}{2\tau_{D}}e^{-t/\tau_{D}}\int_{0}^{t}\left|z(t^{\prime})\right|e^{t/\tau_{D}}\textrm{d}t^{\prime}\label{eq:ePeakDetection}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{D}$
\end_inset 

 being the time constant of the envelope detection.
 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
collapsed true

\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pictures/agc.ps
	lyxscale 50
	height 7cm
	keepAspectRatio

\end_inset 


\layout Caption

Automatic Gain Control.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fAGC}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset 

 is then compared to the amplitude setpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 The error signal 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)-A_{0}$
\end_inset 

, after being fed into a PI (Proportional-Integral) system 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{etique-automatique,silva-PI,Wang-PI}

\end_inset 

, is used to change the variable gain 
\begin_inset Formula $R(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 Both the Proportional gain 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{P}^{AGC}$
\end_inset 

 (controlling the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

stiffness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 of the AGC loop) and the Integration gain 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{I}^{AGC}$
\end_inset 

 (controlling the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

viscosity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 of the AGC loop) can be set by the user.
 One obtains the dynamic gain 
\begin_inset Formula $R(t)$
\end_inset 

:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
R(t)=K_{P}^{AGC}\left[A(t)-A_{0}\right]+K_{I}^{AGC}\int_{-\infty}^{t}\left[A(t')-A_{0}\right]\; dt'\label{eq:eAGC}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Without tip-surface interaction, 
\begin_inset Formula $R(D\rightarrow\infty)=\frac{k_{c}\, A_{0}}{Q_{c}}$
\end_inset 

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{pll}=1.$
\end_inset 


\layout Subsubsection

Frequency demodulation and cantilever excitation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Frequency-demodulation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
collapsed false

\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pictures/pll.ps
	lyxscale 50
	height 7cm
	keepAspectRatio

\end_inset 


\layout Caption

Phase Locked Loop
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fPLL}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Far from any tip-surface interaction, the pulsation 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{pll}(t)$
\end_inset 

 of the PLL (see figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fPLL}

\end_inset 

) reference signal is set by the user to the free frequency of the cantilever
 such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{pll}(t)=\omega_{0}$
\end_inset 

.
 The VCO (Voltage Controlled Oscillator), inside the PLL, produces this
 reference signal by the integration of the input voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t)$
\end_inset 

: 
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\omega_{pll}(t)\, t=\omega_{0}\, t+\int_{-\infty}^{t}\Delta\omega(t')\; dt'=\omega_{0}\, t+K_{0}\int_{-\infty}^{t}u(t')\; dt'\label{eq:eVCO}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset 

 (in Hz) is the conversion factor (voltage to frequency) of the VCO 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{loppacherPLL}

\end_inset 

.
\layout Standard

The signal 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t)$
\end_inset 

 which is proportional to the detuning, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega(t)=\omega(t)-\omega_{0}$
\end_inset 

, of the cantilever frequency, is obtained by low-pass filtering the product
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)$
\end_inset 

 of the reference signal by the cantilever signal 
\begin_inset Formula $z(t)$
\end_inset 

 coming from the photodiode.
 Hence:
\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p(t)=z(t)\, A_{pll}\,\cos(\omega_{pll}(t)\, t+\varphi_{pll})\label{eq:qProduct}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

In first approximation, if we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $z(t)=A(t)\:\sin(\omega(t)\, t+\varphi)$
\end_inset 

, one obtains:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p(t)=\frac{A_{limited}\, A_{pll}}{2}\,\left[\sin((\omega(t)-\omega_{pll}(t))\, t+(\varphi-\varphi_{pll}))+\sin((\omega(t)+\omega_{pll}(t))\, t+(\varphi+\varphi_{pll}))\right]\label{eq:eProduct2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

with a limiter circuit, at the input of the PLL, that limits the signal
 amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $A(t)$
\end_inset 

 to a constant level 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{limited}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

This signal 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)$
\end_inset 

 then goes through a second order low-pass filter defined by two time constants
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{2}$
\end_inset 

:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
p_{1}(t)=\left[\frac{1}{\tau_{1}}\int^{t}p(t')\exp\left(\frac{t'}{\tau_{1}}\right)\; dt'\right]\exp\left(\frac{-t}{\tau_{1}}\right)\label{eq:eLowPass1}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u(t)=G\,\left[\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\int^{t}p_{1}(t')\exp\left(\frac{t'}{\tau_{2}}\right)\; dt'\right]\exp\left(\frac{-t}{\tau_{2}}\right)\label{eq:eLowPass2}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Thanks to this low-pass filter, the low frequency part, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(t)-\omega_{pll}(t)$
\end_inset 

, of the signal 
\begin_inset Formula $p(t)$
\end_inset 

 is extracted.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset 

 allows to adjust the loop gain of the PLL in order to find the good stability-p
recision compromise 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{loppacher-dissertation}

\end_inset 

.
 Hence:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u(t)=G\,\frac{A_{limited}\, A_{pll}}{2}\,\sin((\omega(t)-\omega_{pll}(t))\, t+(\varphi-\varphi_{pll}))\label{eq:eU}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

When 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{pll}(t)=\omega(t)$
\end_inset 

, the PLL is locked on the cantilever frequency.
 So, one can write, in the case of small changes 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\varphi=\varphi-\varphi_{pll}$
\end_inset 

:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
u(t)\simeq G\,\frac{A_{limited}\, A_{pll}}{2}\,\Delta\varphi\label{eq:eUphy}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

giving the frequency detuning 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\omega(t)=K_{0}\, u(t)$
\end_inset 

.
\layout Subsubsection

Distance regulation
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Distance-regulation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
collapsed false

\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pictures/adc.ps
	lyxscale 50
	height 7cm
	keepAspectRatio

\end_inset 


\layout Caption

Automatic Distance Control.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{fADC}

\end_inset 


\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f(t)=\frac{\Delta\omega(t)}{2\pi}$
\end_inset 

 signal coming from the frequency demodulator (see figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fPLL}

\end_inset 

) is used to regulate the distance 
\begin_inset Formula $D(t)$
\end_inset 

 between the cantilever and the surface in order to satisfy the frequency
 setpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f_{c}$
\end_inset 

 (see figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fADC}

\end_inset 

) defined by the user 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{albrecht-fmdemodul,durig-fmdemodul}

\end_inset 

.
 Following this rule, one gets the following expression:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
D(t)=D_{1}+K_{P}^{ADC}\left[\Delta f(t)-\Delta f_{c}\right]+K_{I}^{ADC}\int_{-\infty}^{t}\left[\Delta f(t')-\Delta f_{c}\right]\; dt'\label{eq:eADC}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

where we find, like in the AGC (see equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:eAGC}

\end_inset 

), a PI (Proportional-Integral) system with gains 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{P}^{ADC}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{I}^{ADC}$
\end_inset 

 defined by the user.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset 

 is an ajustable offset in distance.
\layout Subsection

Influence of experimental noises on AFM images
\layout Standard

Another useful application of the virtual AFM is the realistic evaluation
 of the limitations imposed by the noise generated by the components of
 the system.
 Sources of noise in beam deflection AFM have been discussed in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{sarid}

\end_inset 

.
 The major ones are 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{yaralioglu-allnoises}

\end_inset 

:
\layout Standard

The thermal noise of the cantilever 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{cleland-cantilevernoise,albrecht-fmdemodul}

\end_inset 

, whose power spectral density reads: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_{F}(f)=\frac{4\, k_{B}\, T\, k}{2\pi\, f_{0}\, Q}\qquad\textrm{in }N^{2}.Hz^{-1}\label{eForceNoise}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 with the temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset 

, the Boltzmann constant 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{B}$
\end_inset 

.
 In virtual AFM, this noise is implemented at left in equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{eq:eDynamic}

\end_inset 

 as a noise force.
\layout Standard

The amplitude shot noise 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{bacon-shotnoise,yaralioglu-allnoises}

\end_inset 

 of one photodiode quadrant detector: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_{A}^{shot-noise}(f)=2\, q_{e}\, V_{ph}\, R_{trans}\, G_{opt}^{2}\qquad\textrm{in }m^{2}.Hz^{-1}\label{eAmplitudeShotNoise}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

with the elementary charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{e}$
\end_inset 

, the photodiode voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{ph}$
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset Formula $1\, Volt$
\end_inset 

 in our experimental conditions), the transimpedance resistor 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{trans}$
\end_inset 

 (
\begin_inset Formula $500\, k\Omega$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Omicron}

\end_inset 

).
 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{opt}$
\end_inset 

 is a factor to convert the cantilever oscillation in volts coming from
 the photodiode in nanometers.
 It depends of the geometrical design of the optical detection but also
 of the kind of light source used (Laser, LED, ...).
 In our case, we measured 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{opt}=400\, nm.V^{-1}$
\end_inset 

.
 
\layout Standard

Finally, the Johnson noise of the resistor of the current-voltage converter
 that monitors the photodiodes: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_{A}^{Johnson}(f)=4\, k_{B}\, T\, R_{trans}\, G_{opt}^{2}\qquad\textrm{in }m^{2}.Hz^{-1}\label{eAmplitudeJohnsonNoise}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The amplitude shot noise and Johnson noise are both used as amplitude noises
 inside 
\begin_inset Formula $z(t)$
\end_inset 

 the vertical displacement of the cantilever coming from the photodiode
 signal.
\layout Subsection

How one can find parameters of the virtual AFM
\layout Standard

The aim of the virtual machine is to mimic the dynamic of a true experimental
 AFM system.
 In this subsection we shall briefly describe a response of the whole machine
 (Omicron RT-AFM with an easyPLL Nanosurf Demodulator) on a square periodic
 offset added to the distance signal 
\begin_inset Formula $D(t)$
\end_inset 

.
 This is an example of how one can experimentally find the correct parameters
 needed to run the virtual AFM machine.
\layout Standard

Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fCompareExpNum}

\end_inset 

 (a) shows the frequency response to a periodic square excitation added
 to the surface-tip distance 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset 

 while the microscope was in operation above a 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm MoS_{2}}$
\end_inset 

 substrate covered by silver clusters.
 This measurement was performed for two different settings of the ADC feedback
 loop.
 A loop gain of 2% (slow response) corresponds to the typical value for
 normal imaging while a loop gain of 20% (fast response) is only used when
 approaching the surface at the beginning of the experiment.
 The asymmetry of the response between a positive and negative 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta f$
\end_inset 

 (the positive peak is smaller and wider than the negative one) is a consequence
 of the increase of the absolute value of the slope of the van der Waals
 interaction when the tip approaches the surface.
\layout Standard

Fig.
 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{fCompareExpNum}

\end_inset 

 (b) shows the response calculated with the virtual AFM modelling the tip
 by a sphere of the radius 20 nm and taking into account only the van der
 Waals interaction between tyhe tip and sample, with a Hamaker constant
 of 1 eV.
 The experimental behaviour can be well reproduced by choosing the parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{P}^{ADC}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{I}^{ADC}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite{Wang-PI}

\end_inset 

.
 The shape of the peaks is qualitatively correct while the time constants,
 ranging from a few milliseconds at 20% to a few tens of milliseconds at
 2%, are of the same order of magnitude as in the experiment.
 
