\layout Subsubsection

Atomic Coordinates
\begin_inset LatexCommand \label{sub:Atomic-Coordinates}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The rest of the coordinates input box is used to input the positions of
 the atoms in the system in cartesian coordinates.
 Every atom is entered in the same format, but each belongs to one of five
 classes of atoms depending on the keyword used at the beginning of its
 group.
 The five keywords are: 
\layout Itemize


\series bold 
cluster-atoms 
\series default 
- relaxed, contributes to potential and image interactions.
 Usually used to represent relaxed atoms in a cluster.
\layout Itemize


\series bold 
cluster-buffer 
\series default 
- frozen, contributes to potential and image interactions.
 Usually used to represent frozen atoms in a cluster.
\layout Itemize


\series bold 
tip-atoms 
\series default 
- relaxed, contributes to potential and image interactions.
 Included in all operations on the tip (
\series bold 
move, rotate
\series default 
).
 Usually used to represent relaxed atoms in the tip.
\layout Itemize


\series bold 
tip-buffer 
\series default 
- frozen, contributes to potential and image interactions.
 Included in all operations on the tip (
\series bold 
move, rotate
\series default 
).
 Usually used to represent frozen atoms in the tip.
\layout Itemize


\series bold 
frozen-tip
\series default 
 - frozen, contributes to potential interactions, but is removed from image
 calculations.
 Included in all operations on the tip (
\series bold 
move, rotate
\series default 
).
 Usually used to represent frozen atoms in the tip which are within the
 conducting sphere and are forbidden from the contributing to the image
 interaction.
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip 
These groups can only appear once each in the coordinates section, although
 the order in which they appear is irrelevant.
 The format of entry of the coordinates is as follows:
\layout Standard

Element1 x y z (iRx iRy iRz)
\layout Standard

Element2 x y z (iRx iRy iRz)
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom bigskip 
etc.....
\layout Standard
\noindent 
The parameters 
\family typewriter 
iRx
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRy
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRz
\family default 
 control whether an atom is allowed to relax in the x, y, z directions respectiv
ely - 0 0 0 would fix the atom in all three directions.
 They are optional and do not need to be specified.
 The default values for 
\family typewriter 
iRx
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRy
\family default 
, 
\family typewriter 
iRz
\family default 
 are taken from the group the atoms belong to e.g.
 all
\series bold 
 tip- 
\series default 
and
\series bold 
 cluster-atoms 
\series default 
atoms are relaxed by default.
 The relaxation flags for shells are obtained appropriately from the 
\series bold 
shell
\series default 
 option (section 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::shells}

\end_inset 

).
\layout Subsection

Interactions between atoms
\layout Subsubsection

ShellPar Box
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip 

\series bold 
\emph on 
Box Keyword
\series default 
\emph default 
: 
\family typewriter 
.<ShellPar>
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom bigskip 
This box is used to input the charges and masses on atoms and their shells
 (in electron charge and atomic mass units respectively), along with the
 spring constant between them (in Newton metres).
 It has the following format:
\layout Standard

Element1 
\begin_inset Formula $M{}_{core}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{core}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $M{}_{shell}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{shell}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

Element2 
\begin_inset Formula $M{}_{core}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{core}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $M{}_{shell}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{shell}$
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 


\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom bigskip 
etc ....
\layout Standard
\noindent 
where Element1, Element2, etc.
 are the atomic element names from the periodic table.
 The element name can also include a numerical identifier as a third character,
 e.g.
 Mg1, to differentiate between the same atom species with different interactions.
 This can be used to model atoms of the same species in the surface and
 tip differently.
 
\layout Standard

Any atoms which have both a 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{core}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{shell}$
\end_inset 

 will have a shell created automatically and positioned at the same place
 as the initial atom coordinates.
 This will then be free to relax independently of the original atom to represent
 electronic polarization.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $Q{}_{shell}$
\end_inset 

 is zero then no shell will exist for this element.
 If an energy minimisation is being performed, then the values provided
 for the core and shell masses will be ignored.
 
\layout Standard

During an MD simulation shell dynamics is handled by one of two algorithms,
 specified in the MDcontrol box, either the fictitious dynamic shell model
 or the relaxed shell model (sections 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::Geometry-optimisation-options}

\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{Sec::MDcontrol-Box}

\end_inset 

).
 In the first of these, any shells must be given a (usually small) mass,
 so that equations of motion can be integrated.
 In the second, shells are relaxed at every timestep and require no mass
 (if a mass is provided it will be ignored).
 
\layout Subsubsection

PairPotenc Box
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom smallskip 

\series bold 
\emph on 
Box Keyword
\series default 
\emph default 
: 
\family typewriter 
.<PairPotenc>
\layout Standard

This box contains the parameters which control the interactions (excluding
 electrostatic charge-charge interactions which are calculated implicitly)
 between atoms in the system.
 It must contain an entry for each pair of elements including itself.
 If a pair is entered twice, only the first pair will be used.
 The following general short-range interaction can be used:
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V(r)=\sum_{i}C_{i}r^{-n_{i}}+\sum_{j}A_{j}e^{-\frac{r}{\rho_{j}}}\label{potential_eq}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom bigskip \noindent 
If you wish to use a cutoff (in 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA
\end_inset 

) for the interactions, then the keyword 
\series bold 
cutoff
\series default 
 must be the first entry in the pairpotenc box.
 If this keyword is not present then the cutoffs entered in the pair interaction
s will be ignored (in other words you do not need to enter any) and the
 interaction will be across the entire system.
 However, an error will be produced if the 
\series bold 
cutoff
\series default 
 keyword is used, but cutoff values for every pair are not present.
 The parameters of the one pair's interaction are entered in the following
 format:
\layout Standard

Element1 Element2 (cutoff)
\layout Standard


\series bold 
exp 
\series default 
#
\layout Standard


\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}\;\rho_{j}$
\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard


\series bold 
pow
\series default 
 #
\layout Standard
\added_space_bottom bigskip 

\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}\; n_{i}$
\end_inset 

 
\layout Standard
\noindent 
The number # after 
\series bold 
exp
\series default 
 and 
\series bold 
pow
\series default 
 specifies the number of exponential and power terms in the interaction
 respectively.
 The appropriate number of parameters must then follow below, remembering
 that all values should be entered in units of 
\begin_inset ERT
status Collapsed

\layout Standard

\backslash 
AA{ 
\end_inset 

of distance and eV of energy.
